er, but much of his book is directed to writers such as Homer and the tragedians, whom he discusses as poets and not just as materials for philosophy. At the center of his study is the question of how we can understand Greek tragedy at all, when its world is so far from ours. Williams explains how it is that when the ancients speak, they do not merely tell us about themselves, but about ourselves. In a new foreword A.A. Long explores the impact of this volume in the context of Williams's stunning career.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEthics in literature. 0aGreek poetryxHistory and criticism. 0aNecessity (Philosophy) in literature. 0aPhilosophy, Ancient, in literature. 0aShame in literature. 4aAncient Archaeology. 4aAncient History. 4aEuropean literature. 4aGreeks. 4aHomer. 4aancient Greek history. 4aancient philosophy. 4aclassical antiquity. 4aclassical literature. 4aethics. 4afreedom. 4ahistory of art. 4ahistory of philosophy. 4ahistory of the Americas. 4ahistory of western philosophy. 4ahistory. 4aidea. 4aliberty. 4aliterature. 4amoral philosophy. 4amoral. 4aphilosophy. 4apolitical philosophy. 4aresponsibility. 4asocial philosophy. 4athe arts. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aancient classical.  aancient greece.  aancient greek ethics.  aancient greeks.  aancient history and classics.  aancient philosophy.  aancient poetry.  aancient poets.  aaristotle.  aclassical philosophy.  aclassical studies.  aethics and moral philosophy.  aethics and morality.  aethics in literature.  aethics.  agreek literature.  agreek poetry.  agreek studies.  agreek tragedy.  agreeks.  ahistory of philosophy.  ahomer.  aliterary criticism.  aliterature of antiquity.  anecessity in literature.